outlooksByWeek.1: Jahmyr Gibbs and co-starter David Montgomery will work to reprise as the league's most effective backfield duo, beginning Week 1 on the road against Green Bay. New OC John Morton spent the offseason emphasizing Gibbs' pass-catching abilities, even splitting him out wide at practices, and after the 2023 third-round pick's truly dominant performance as a workhorse from Week 13 onward last season, when Montgomery went down to an MCL injury, Detroit could be motivated to feature him more heavily than in an actual even split. While the loss of Ben Johnson figures to detract from the Lions' overall efficiency on offense, and the offseason retirement of C Frank Ragnow will be difficult to overcome, Gibbs remains in prime position to repeat as one of the league's most productive ball carriers. He and Montgomery could be the feature of the Lions' gameplan Week 1, as Green Bay ranked third in the league against the pass last season but middle-of-the-road against the run.
outlooksByWeek.2: Jahmyr Gibbs and David Montgomery will work to return to their usual form as a dominant Lions backfield duo in Week 2 versus the Bears. Detroit's offense as a whole will be working to bounce back after an embarrassing Week 1 showing against the Packers' defense, though it was particularly surprising to see Gibbs turn nine carries and 10 targets into just 50 scoreless yards. His 31 receiving yards were, in fact, an NFL record as the lowest total yardage a player has managed on 10 or more targets, and his 2.1 YPC mark was worse than any single game of his 2024 season, playoffs included. Gibbs and Montgomery split carries essentially evenly, and while Gibbs projects for more work in the receiving game, he's only logged double-digit targets on one other occasion in his career. He'll need to return his usual hallmark efficiency versus Chicago in order to return on his expectations as a top-five fantasy draft pick.
outlooksByWeek.3: Jahmyr Gibbs and the Lions travel to Baltimore in Week aA�3, coming off a big 52-21 win over the Bears in WeekaA�2 where he totaled 12 carries for 94 yards and one touchdown, adding three receptions for 10 yards through the air. The electric running back showcased his usual dynamic playmaking ability, an encouraging development after he (along with the rest of Detroit's offense) was held in check by Green Bay in Week 1. The Ravens' front seven is more stout than Chicago's, but Gibbs' versatility and playmaking skills give him a clear path to RB1 value, particularly in PPR formats if the Lions are forced to rely on him more on early downs versus a Baltimore secondary better capable of containing Amon-Ra St. Brown and Jameson Williams.
outlooksByWeek.4: Jahmyr Gibbs will look to keep up his momentum as he and the Lions travel to Cleveland in Week 4, coming off a monster showing in Detroit's 38-30 Monday Night Football win over the Ravens. Gibbs handled a true workhorse role with 22 carries for 67 yards and two touchdowns, while also catching five of six targets for 32 yards. Detroit leaned on him heavily in the red zone, where his explosiveness translated into two short scores, and his involvement in the passing game again underlined his dual-threat value. Cleveland's front is among the NFL's toughest, but Gibbs' versatility and guaranteed workload lock him in as an RB1, even in a matchup where efficiency may be hard to come by. Interestingly, Detroit handed Gibbs nearly double the carries of backfield mate David Montgomery in Week 3, allowing the latter to stay fresher and demonstrate more big-play ability.
outlooksByWeek.5: Jahmyr Gibbs brings a workhorse role into the Lions Week 5 matchup with the Bengals. Gibbs has seen at least 15 touches in each of Detroit's first four games, and while his 4.7 ypc is the lowest of his three-year career, the volume paired with four touchdowns makes him an every week starter. That's amplified by the matchup, as the Bengals have allowed the third-most fantasy points to opposing running backs to date, and 100-yard rushers in each of the last two weeks.
outlooksByWeek.6: Jahmyr Gibbs rushed the ball 12 times for 54 yards in the 37-24 win over the Bengals in Week 5, and he also added two catches for 33 yards and a touchdown, showing he continues to make an impact as a two-way threat out of the backfield. Gibbs continues to split the workload with David Montgomery in the Lions' backfield, but it's worth noting that he has still found the end zone in four straight games while surpassing 85 scrimmage yards in each of those contests. Even if he continues to operate in a timeshare with Montgomery, Gibbs has strong RB1 upside ahead of this Week 6 matchup against the Chiefs due to his versatility and ability to make an impact both as a rusher and receiver out of the backfield. The fact that Kansas City ranks as a slightly below-average defense against the run in fantasy should boost Gibbs' upside even more.
outlooksByWeek.7: Jahmyr Gibbs has been far less explosive than he was last season with 4.5 yards per carry and 4.9 yards per reception, compared to 5.6 and 9.9 marks in 2024. His receiving usage has begun to drop off recently, too, getting targeted just six times over the last three games, although the Lions won two of those games handedly. Gibbs could get a much better opportunity in Week 7 against the Buccaneers -- the league's 24th-ranked scoring defense. Although the Bucs have the fifth-ranked run defense, they also have a high-powered offense that could turn this game into a shootout, which would bode well for Gibbs, as he should get targeted frequently if that transpires.
outlooksByWeek.9: Jahmyr Gibbs delivered a dominant performance when the Lions defeated the Buccaneers in Week 7 just before the bye, tallying 17 carries for 136 yards and a pair of touchdowns while adding three receptions for 82 yards. That was the first time he recorded over 200 yards from scrimmage in a single game in his career, but he's not expected to monopolize the backfield workload at that rate going forward since the Lions also have David Montgomery as an option. Still, Gibbs should start in all formats until further notice due to his ability as both a rushing threat and a receiving outlet. The Vikings have allowed the 12th-fewest fantasy points to RBs in 2025.

player.seasonOutlook: The reigning No. 1 fantasy RB, Gibbs scored a position-high 20 TDs while dominating as both a rusher (fifth in yards) and receiver (top six in targets, catches and yards) last season. The with/without David Montgomery splits are notable here, however, as Gibbs averaged 16.3 touches and 18.2 fantasy points per game (sixth best) in 13 games with a healthy Montgomery, but 22.5 touches and 31.5 points per game (first) without. Montgomery is back, so Gibbs' touch ceiling may be slightly lower than a few other top backs, but with his skill set and Detroit's high-powered offense, he's undoubtedly a strong fantasy RB1. The 23-year-old should be one of the first players off the board on draft day.

outlooksByWeek.1: Ja'Marr Chase's start to his career has been exceptional while serving as the Bengals' top pass catcher, but he took a leap forward in 2024 by posting 127 receptions, 1,708 yards and 17 total touchdowns. While those numbers may not be repeatable, Chase has at least 80 catches and 1,000 yards in all four of his pro seasons. He's tremendously safe heading into a Week 1 matchup the Browns to the begin the 2025 campaign and should be started without question.
outlooksByWeek.2: Ja'Marr Chase had arguably the most disappointing fantasy showing in Week 1, as the entire Cincinnati offense fell flat. However, neither his skill nor role is in doubt heading into a Week 2 matchup against Jacksonville, making him an easy choice to put together a bounce back performance. Chase is a must-start option despite his subpar start to the 2025 season.
outlooksByWeek.3: Ja'Marr Chase rebounded from a subpar Week 1 performance to power the Bengals' offense in a Week 2 win. The absence of Joe Burrow (toe) is a concern, but Chase managed 10 receptions for 128 yards once Jake Browning entered Sunday's game. He draws a tough Week 3 matchup against the Vikings, which will further limit the likelihood of Chase turning in another ceiling performance, but his talent and role in the offense keep him locked in as a solid WR1.
outlooksByWeek.4: Ja'Marr Chase led the Bengals in targets, receptions and yards with Jake Browning taking over as the leader of the offense in Week 3. However, Browning was hesitant to push the ball down the field, causing targets to be distributed more heavily to tight ends and backs than is typically the case, while also devaluing the opportunities Chase collected. A Week 4 matchup against the Broncos is another reason for concern, as the Broncos have allowed only one wide receiver to top 80 receiving yards through three games. While the likelihood of a top-end outcome has certainly declined for Chase, he remains a must-start option at wide receiver.
outlooksByWeek.5: Ja'Marr Chase remains the primary target in the Bengals' offense, but the unit has looked like the league's worst under the leadership of Jake Browning. In Browning's two starts, Chase has earned a reasonable 14 targets, but that's translated into only 73 yards with no touchdowns. Chase is still a viable option in Week 5 against Detroit due to his talent and guaranteed role, but he's clearly not the fantasy difference maker that he was drafted to be during the preseason. Expect a WR2 showing.
outlooksByWeek.6: Ja'Marr Chase has been held back by the absence of Joe Burrow (foot), but Chase was able to showcase his game-breaking ability with a pair of touchdowns in Week 5. While he had previously failed to show his typical upside, Chase maintained a reasonable floor by recording at least five catches in three straight games in the Cincinnati offense. His outlook for Week 6 against Green Bay may not be conducive to another spike performance, as the Packers have allowed only two wide receivers to top 50 receiving yards in a game. Chase is still a WR1, but he's unlikely to keep pace with other elite pass catchers around the league.
outlooksByWeek.7: Ja'Marr Chase didn't take long to show rapport with Joe Flacco, earning 12 targets -- Chase's second-highest mark of the season. He was limited to short areas of the field for most of the game, but he made an acrobatic 19-yard touchdown late in the fourth quarter. Chase now heads into a Week 7 matchup against the Steelers posting at least 90 yards and a touchdown in each of his last two games. Pittsburgh has improved defensively in recent weeks, but Chase is still a must-start WR1 option.
outlooksByWeek.8: Ja'Marr Chase showcased his ability as one of the best receivers in the league with a standout effort against the Steelers in Week 7, topping 100 receiving yards and reaching double-digit receptions for the third time this season. In two games since Joe Flacco has taken over the Bengals' offense, Chase has 35 targets, 255 yards and 26 catches combined. While Chase hasn't been particularly efficient, it's clear that Flacco is going to target him constantly, and fantasy points are likely to follow. A Week 8 matchup against the Jets could be tough with Sauce Gardner (concussion) likely to cover Chase, but Gardner is currently in concussion protocol so his progress throughout the week will be worth monitoring. Regardless, Chase is a must start fantasy receiver and has the potential to be the most productive player at the position every week.
outlooksByWeek.9: Ja'Marr Chase and Joe Flacco have shown immediate chemistry, as Chase has drawn a minimum of 12 targets in three games with Flacco under center. There haven't been many explosive plays -- none of his 38 receptions have gone for 20 yards or more -- but Chase has scored twice in those three contests with double-digit catches in each. The Bengals will take on the Bears in Week 9, and Chicago has been a defense effectively limiting opposing volume, as the unit has surrendered both the second-fewest targets and receptions to opposing wide receivers for the campaign. While Chase may not quite be able to keep up his excellent pace of the last few games, he remains a locked-in WR1 and has the chance to be the top scoring pass catcher every week.

player.seasonOutlook: The reigning No. 1 fantasy receiver, Chase outscored second-place Justin Jefferson by a massive 85.5 points. His career year included nine top-10 fantasy weeks (three more than any other receiver), as well as the most routes, targets, receptions, yards, touchdowns and end zone targets (17) in the league. He has finished in the top 12 in fantasy PPG in all four of his NFL seasons, including top 5 in three of them. Chase became the league's highest-paid non-quarterback during the offseason and is a heavily targeted 25-year-old superstar on the league's pass-heaviest offense with an elite QB in Joe Burrow. He should be the first WR off the board and is a strong option with the No. 1 overall pick.

outlooksByWeek.1: Amon-Ra St. Brown and the Lions will kick off the season Week 1 on the road against Green Bay, who parted ways with top cornerback Jaire Alexander this offseason. Concerns about Detroit's efficiency on offense are valid - the team lost two of last year's starters along the O-line, as well as former OC Ben Johnson, but St. Brown has been one of the league's most consistent producers since entering the league as a fourth-round pick in 2021, with three consecutive 1,000-yard seasons under his belt, and back-to-back years with double-digit TDs. The Packers ranked third against the pass last season, though, and even without Alexander in the secondary, the addition of All-Pro pass rusher Micah Parsons presents a new challenge for Jared Goff and the aerial attack. As such, to start the year, it wouldn't be surprising for St. Brown, Jameson Williams and TE Sam LaPorta to take a slight backseat, while RBs Jahmyr Gibbs and David Montgomery lead the gameplan on offense.
outlooksByWeek.2: Amon-Ra St. Brown and the Lions will host the Bears in Week 2, as he aims to build on a modest Week 1 performance. He caught four passes on six targets for 45 yards in Detroit's opener, a quiet start but one that belies his central role in Jared Goff's passing game. St. Brown lines up predominantly in the slot, which gives him a potential mismatch against the Bears' less experienced interior corners, leaving Jameson Williams to contend more directly with Jaylon Johnson. With defensive attention further spread by Jahmyr Gibbs and David Montgomery in the backfield, St. Brown should be poised for a bounce-back performance with new OC John Morton extra motivated to prove the departure of Ben Johnson (to Chicago) hasn't left him outmatched.
outlooksByWeek.3: Amon-Ra St. Brown and the Lions travel to Baltimore in Week aA�3, coming off a monster 52-21 win over the Bears in Week 2 in which he hauled in nine receptions for 113 yards and three touchdowns. He also rushed twice for seven yards in the blowout win, while definitively leading the team in terms of catches, targets, receiving yards and scores. St. Brown dominated coverage with crisp route running and strong hands, showing his ability to be a true field-stretching threat even with the defense keying on him. Baltimore presents a more disciplined secondary, but St. Brown's volume and red-zone usage make him a high-end WR1, especially following a convincing demonstration that the departure of OC Ben Johnson hasn't detracted from his high-end upside.
outlooksByWeek.4: Amon-Ra St. Brown and the Lions travel to Cleveland in Week 4, coming off another strong Monday Night Football win over the Ravens. As usual, the start wideout served as Jared Goff's most reliable weapon, moving the chains with precision route running and providing key plays to keep drives alive. While David Montgomery and Jahmyr Gibbs stole the spotlight with explosive ground production, St. Brown continued to operate as the centerpiece of the passing attack. Against Cleveland's secondary, which is one of the more disciplined units in football, volume and efficiency will be key, but St. Brown's heavy target share cements him as a locked-in WR1 regardless of matchup.
outlooksByWeek.5: Amon-Ra St. Brown has been a touchdown machine ahead of the Lions Week 5 game against the Bengals. St. Brown scored twice last week on seven targets, now seeing at least six looks in every game to date and tallying six scores through four games. While Detroit is heavily favored and may not need to pass as often, St. Brown has proven game script proof, and can be trusted as a WR1 against a defense that's already allowed eight different opposing receivers to top 50 yards against them.
outlooksByWeek.6: Amon-Ra St. Brown recorded eight receptions on nine targets for 100 yards in the Lions' win over the Bengals in Week 5, and this was the second time the star wideout recorded at least 100 receiving yards in a game in 2025. The undisputed go-to option in the passing game for QB Jared Goff, St. Brown has a very high floor and high upside every time he steps on the gridiron, so he should retain WR1 upside and must-start status for this Week 6 matchup against the Chiefs, especially since Kansas City ranks as a middle-of-the-pack defense against the pass in fantasy this season.
outlooksByWeek.7: Amon-Ra St. Brown ranks sixth in the league with 452 receiving yards through six games, and he's tied for the league lead with six receiving touchdowns. His targets have been steady with 8.5 per game. The Lions have faced the Buccaneers twice over the last two seasons, and St. Brown exploded in those outings with 23 receptions for 243 yards and a touchdown. He's set up quite well again in Week 7, as the Buccaneers have the 21st-ranked pass defense and 24th-ranked scoring defense this year.
outlooksByWeek.9: Amon-Ra St. Brown caught six of 10 targets for 86 yards and a touchdown in the Lions' win over the Buccaneers in Week 7 just before the bye, ending a two-game stretch without finding the end zone. Even though St. Brown isn't among the league leaders in receiving touchdowns, the star wideout is the clear-cut No. 1 wideout in Detroit, and he provides enough value as it is due to his target share and excellent catch rates. St. Brown's mini scoring slump hasn't stopped him from posting WR1-level numbers this season, as he heads into a Week 9 matchup against the Vikings holding a 50-538-7 receiving line.

player.seasonOutlook: St. Brown enters his fifth NFL campaign as the only player in the league with 105 or more receptions each of the past three seasons. Compared to 2023, St. Brown actually saw a decrease in targets, receptions and yards last season, but offset some of that with a career-high 12 touchdowns and still finished as the No. 3 fantasy WR for the second year in a row. He remains an elite, short-range target, having paced qualified wide receivers in catch rate (81%) in 2024 and having now ranked top 5 in first downs per route run for the third year in a row. The 25-year-old is a heavily utilized target in one of the league's best offenses and a clear top-5 fantasy wide receiver.
